(ANS=19.87554)

video

First, determine the mean of the sample.

\[\bar{x} = \frac{\sum \mathbf{x}}{n} =50.89 \]

Determine the squared deviations (squared distances from \(\bar{x}\)).

\[i\] \[\mathbf{x}\] deviations = \(\mathbf{x}-\bar{x}\) SqrDev = \((\mathbf{x}-\bar{x})^2\)
1 43.46 -7.43 55.2049
2 54.98 4.09 16.7281
3 54.97 4.08 16.6464
4 50.98 0.09 0.0081
5 54.04 3.15 9.9225
6 52.96 2.07 4.2849
7 54.81 3.92 15.3664
8 51.15 0.26 0.0676
9 42.02 -8.87 78.6769
10 49.53 -1.36 1.8496

Now, take the mean of the squared deviations.

\[\text{VAR} = \frac{\sum (\mathbf{x}-\bar{x})^2}{n} = 19.87554 \]

spreadsheet

You can do this with a spreadsheet.


And, actually, you can skip a lot of work by using the VAR.P function. Using the population variance formula is equivalent to using the biased sample variance formula.

R

You can do this with R

x = read.csv("get_VAR.csv")$x
xbar = mean(x)
deviations = x-xbar
sqrdev = deviations^2
VAR = mean(sqrdev)

# The built-in var() function almost works, but it is too fancy, and makes a Bessel correction. To use it, we need to undo the Bessel correction.
n = length(x)
var(x)*(n-1)/(n)
## [1] 19.87554
